<section class="expert-concepts">
    <h2>Key Concepts from Dr. Dayspring</h2>

    <div class="concept-list">
        <div class="concept-item">
            <h3>LDL Particle Number (LDL-P)</h3>
            <p>The actual number of LDL particles, measured by NMR spectroscopy. More predictive of risk than LDL cholesterol content.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="concept-item">
            <h3>ApoB</h3>
            <p>Apolipoprotein B-100, one molecule per atherogenic particle. Directly measures all particles that can enter the artery wall.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="concept-item">
            <h3>Discordance</h3>
            <p>When LDL-C and LDL-P don't match. In discordant cases, particle number predicts cardiovascular events better than cholesterol content.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="concept-item">
            <h3>Lipoprotein(a) [Lp(a)]</h3>
            <p>A genetically determined, highly atherogenic particle that standard panels don't measure. An independent causal risk factor.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="concept-item">
            <h3>Remnant Lipoproteins</h3>
            <p>Partially metabolized VLDL particles that are highly atherogenic and often elevated in metabolic syndrome.</p>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>

